ce:section.ce:para:
The surface modification and conjugation reactions were monitored by FTIR and solution-phase NMRs. As shown in the FTIR spectrum (Fig. 1
                        ), CDs displayed strong absorption bands centered at 3200 and 1690 cm−1 attributed to the stretching vibrations of OH and CO bonds, indicating the presence of hydroxyl and carboxyl groups on CDs. After grafting CDs with PG, two intense absorption peaks located at 2880 and 1660 cm-1 were detected in the FTIR curve of CD-PG, which are corresponding to the stretching vibrations of C–H and COC bonds of CD-PG. In the FTIR spectrum of CD-PG-COOH, a strong peak at 1730 cm-1 arising from the incorporated carboxyl groups was observed. In the 1H NMR spectrum of CD-PG-COOH (Fig. 2
                        a), the strong resonance peak at 2.7 ppm is ascribed to the protons on the carbons adjacent to CO bonds. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of CD-PG (Fig. 2) revealed resonance peaks similar to those of free PG, but the signals from aromatic carbons of CDs were not detected probably due to the low content. In the 13C NMR spectrum of CD-PG-COOH (Fig. 2b), the resonance peaks at 174 and 176 ppm are corresponding to the CO carbons of ester and carboxyl groups, respectively; the carbons next to the carbonyl groups are found at 29 ppm. Finally, the successful conjugation of CD-PG-COOH and IO-PG-NH2 was evidenced by appearance of characteristic CO and NH stretching vibrations of amide groups located at 1640 and 1555 cm-1, respectively.

The particle size of the nanocomponents and nanohyrids was investigated by transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and dynamic light scattering (DLS). As depicted in Fig. 3
                        a, CD-PG-COOH was well dispersed on the substrate with a tiny core of 2∼3 nm in diameter, whereas IO-PG-NH2 showed a relatively larger core size of about 10 nm. In the TEM image of IO-PG-CD nanohybrid, nanoclusters comprising IO nanoparticles surrounded with many smaller CDs were observed, further confirming the successful construction of the nanohybrid. When dispersed in water, the mean hydrodynamic diameter of IO-PG-CD was measured to be 148.2 ± 10.4 nm (Table 1
                        ), much large than those of CD-PG-COOH (6.7 ± 2.4 nm) and IO-PG-NH2 (36.7 ± 5.9 nm). The DLS results coincide with the TEM observations that IO-PG-CD is in the form of nanoclusters.
